Stocks in India Swing Between Gains, Losses; Wipro Climbs on Acquisition

-- B y   R a j h k u m a r   K   S h a a w
-- 
2011-05-11T11:55:59Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-11/indian-stocks-swing-between-gains-losses-refiners-decline.html
India ’s benchmark stock index rose.
 State Bank of India (SBIN)  paced gains among lenders and metal makers
climbed, tracking an increase in commodity prices.  State Bank  rose 1.8 percent to the highest level in more
than a week. The nation’s biggest bank said it will raise its
benchmark lending rate starting tomorrow. Sterlite Industries
(India) Ltd., the biggest copper producer, jumped 1.6 percent,
rallying for a third day. The  London  Metal Exchange Index of six
metals including copper and aluminum climbed for a third day
yesterday, gaining 0.7 percent. The Bombay Stock Exchange’s
Metal Index has dropped 11 percent this year, compared with a
9.4 percent decline in the benchmark index.  “The recent underperformance of metal stocks, coupled with
an increase in prices in London, attracted buyers,” Sunil Pachisia, vice-president at Mumbai-based brokerage Pratibhuti
Viniyog Ltd., said by phone. He favors shares of  Tata Steel
Ltd. (TATA) , the nation’s largest producer of the alloy, and MOIL Ltd.,
the biggest miner of manganese ore.  The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or Sensex, rose
72.19, or 0.4 percent, to 18,584.96 at the 3:30 p.m. close in
Mumbai. The gauge swung between gains and losses at least nine
times. The S&P CNX Nifty Index on the National Stock Exchange
added 0.4 percent to 5,565.05. Its May futures traded at
5,562.80. The BSE 200 Index increased 0.4 percent to 2,296.14.  The Sensex has declined 9.4 percent this year on concern
higher borrowing costs will hurt corporate earnings. Sensex
stocks trade at an average 14.8 times estimated profit, down
from 21.5 times in March 2010. The MSCI Emerging Markets Index
is valued at 11.4 times.  Lending Rate  India’s central bank May 3 raised the benchmark repurchase
rate by half a percentage point to 7.25 percent, the most since
July 2008, and Governor Duvvuri Subbarao predicted inflation
will stay “elevated” until September.  Oil prices  and monsoon
rainfall will shape inflation, Finance Minister Pranab Mukherjee
said the same day.  State Bank rallied 1.8 percent to 2,675 rupees, the highest
close since May 2. The lender will increase its prime lending
rate by 75 basis points to 14 percent from tomorrow, it said in
an exchange filing after the markets closed yesterday.  HDFC Bank
Ltd. (HDFCB) , the third-largest lender, added 0.7 percent to 2,261.05
rupees.  Sterlite Industries (India) Ltd., the largest copper and
zinc producer, jumped 1.6 percent to 177.15. Tata Steel added 1
percent to 594.2 rupees.  Hindalco Industries Ltd. (HNDL) , the biggest
aluminum producer, increased 0.8 percent to 204.85 rupees.  Beating Estimates  Ranbaxy Laboratories Ltd., the country’s largest drugmaker
by revenue, rallied 6.1 percent to 477.9 rupees, the most since
Feb. 16 last year after reporting first-quarter net income that
beat analysts’ estimates. Net income fell 68 percent to 3.04
billion rupees ($68 million) in the three months ended March.
That exceeded the 1.68 billion-rupee average of 15 analyst
estimates compiled by Bloomberg.  Wipro Ltd. (WPRO) , India’s third-largest software-services
provider, rose 0.7 percent to 439.15 rupees after it agreed to
acquire a majority stake in Brazil-based hydraulic cylinder
maker R.K.M. Equipamentos Hidraulicos Ltda.  DLF Ltd. (DLFU) , India’s biggest developer, rose 2.4 percent to
227.2 rupees, paring this year’s drop to 22 percent.  Hero Honda
Motors Ltd. (HH) , the biggest motorcycle maker, climbed 3.6 percent
to 1,776.15 rupees, the highest close since April 21.  Overseas investors bought a net 2.44 billion rupees ($54.5
million) of Indian stocks on May 9, taking their investments in
equities this year to 18.5 billion rupees, according to data on
the  website  of the  Securities and Exchange Board of India .  To contact the reporter on this story:
